=== Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors ===
[[Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors|SSRIs]] are a class of antidepressants most commonly used in the treatment of depression, and some personality disorders. They have been found as efficient in alleviating hot flashes.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}

=== Isoflavones ===
[[Isoflavones]] are commonly found in [[legume]]s such as soy and red clover. The two soy isoflavones implicated in relieving menopausal symptoms are [[genistein]] and [[daidzein]], and are also known as [[phytoestrogens]]. The half life of these molecules is about eight hours, which might explain why some studies have not consistently shown effectiveness of soy products for menopausal symptoms.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}  Although red clover (''Trifolium pratense'') contains isoflavones similar to soy, the effectiveness of this herb for menopausal symptoms at relatively low concentrations points to a different mechanism of action.<ref>Hani P. Nissan, Jian Lu, Nancy L. Booth, Henry I. Yamamura, Norman R. Farnsworth, Z. Jim Wan. A red clover (Trifolium pratense) phase II clinical extract possesses opiate activity. Journal of Ethnopharmacology 2007; 112:207–210</ref>

=== Other phytoestrogens ===
It is believed that dietary changes that include a higher consumption of [[phytoestrogens]] from sources such as soy, red clover, ginseng, and yam may relieve hot flashes.
* [[Ginseng]]: Very few studies exist on the effect of ginseng for relief of menopausal symptoms. In a large double-blinded randomized controlled trial, reduction in hot flashes was not statistically significant but showed a strong trend towards improvement.<ref>Wiklund IK, Mattsson LA, Lindgren R, Limoni C, for the Swedish Alternative Medicine Group. Effects of a standardized ginseng extract on quality of life and physiological parameters in symptomatic post-menopausal women: a double-blind, placebo-controlled trial. Int J Clin Pharmacol Res. 1999;19:89 –99.</ref>
* [[Flaxseed]]: There have also been several clinical trials using flaxseed. Flaxseed is the richest source of [[lignan]]s, which is one of three major classes of  phytoestrogen.<ref>Basch E, Bent S, Collins J, et al. Flax and flaxseed oil (Linum usitatissimum): a review by the Natural Standard Research Collaboration. J Soc Integr Oncol 2007 Summer;5(3):92–105.</ref> Lignans are thought to have estrogen agonist and antagonist effects as well as antioxidant properties. Flaxseed and its lignans may have potent anti-estrogenic effects on estrogen receptor positive breast cancer and may have benefits in breast cancer prevention efforts.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Jugenström | first = Malin Bergman | last2 = Thompson | first2 = Lilian U. | last3 = Dabrosin | first3 = Charlotta | title = Flaxseed and Its Lignans Inhibit Estradiol-Induced Growth, Angiogenesis, and Secretion of Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor in Human Breast Cancer Xenografts ''In vivo'' | journal = Clinical Cancer Research | volume =13 | issue = 3 | pages =1061-1067 | publisher = American Association for Cancer Research | date = February 1, 2007   | url =http://clincancerres.aacrjournals.org/content/13/3/1061.full.pdf+html | doi = 10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-06-1651 | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name="Dietary Lignan Intake"> {{cite journal | last = Touillaud | first = Marina S. | last2 = Thiébaut | first2 = Anne C. M. | last3 = Fournier | first3 = Agnès | last4 = Niravong | first4 = Maryvonne | last5 = Boutron-Ruault | first5 = Marie-Christine | last6 = Clavel-Chapelon | first6 = Françoise | title = Dietary Lignan Intake and Postmenopausal Breast Cancer Risk by Estrogen and Progesterone Receptor Status | journal = [[Journal of the National Cancer Institute]] | volume = 99 | issue = 6 | pages = 475-486 | publisher = Oxford University Press | date = March 21, 2007 | url = http://jnci.oxfordjournals.org/content/99/6/475.full.pdf+html | issn = 1460-2105 | doi = 10.1093/jnci/djk096 | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref> One recent study done in France, looked at four types of lignans, including that found in flaxseed (Secoisolariciresinol) in a prospective cohort study to see if intake predicted breast cancer incidence.<ref name="Dietary Lignan Intake"/> The authors report lowered risk of breast cancer among over 58,000 postmenopausal women who had the third highest quartile of lignan intake. There have been a few small pilot studies that have tested the effect of flaxseed on hot flashes. Currently there is a large study sponsored by the National Cancer Institute that is ongoing, but not accepting any new participants.<ref>{{cite web | title = Flaxseed in Treating Postmenopausal Women With Hot Flashes Who Have a History of Breast Cancer or Other Cancer or Who Do Not Wish to Take Estrogen Therapy | work = ClinicalTrials.gov | publisher = U.S. National Institute of Health | date = November 2010 | url = http://clinicaltrials.gov/ct2/show/NCT00956813#wrapper | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref> The rationale for the study is that estrogen can relieve the symptoms of menopause, but can also cause the growth of breast cancer cells. Flaxseed may reduce the number of hot flashes and improve mood and quality of life in postmenopausal women not receiving estrogen therapy.

=== Lifestyle changes ===
Lifestyle changes may help alleviate hot flashes. These include avoiding caffeine, hot drinks, chocolate, spicy or hot foods and alcohol.{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}

== In men ==
Hot flashes in men could have various causes. One is a possible sign of low testosterone.<ref>{{cite web | last = Bunyavanich | first = Supinda | title = Low Testosterone Could Kill You | work = ABC News | publisher = ABC News Internet Ventures | date = June 6, 2007 | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Health/ActiveAging/story?id=3247773#.UXKwlcWhhCI | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref> Another is andropause, or "male menopause". <ref name="livestrong.com">{{cite web | last = Holley | first = Casey L. | title = 5 Things You Need to Know About the Causes of Hot Flashes in Men | work = Livestrong.com | publisher = Demand Media Inc. | date = August 11, 2011 | url = http://www.livestrong.com/article/9770-need-causes-hot-flashes-men/ | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref>  Men with [[prostate cancer]] or [[testicular cancer]] can also have hot flashes, especially those who are undergoing hormone therapy with [[antiandrogens]], also known as androgen antagonists, which reduce testosterone to castrate levels.<ref>{{cite web | title = What to Expect During Therapy | work = Lupron Depot | publisher = Abbott Laboratories | url =http://www.lupronadvancedprostatecancer.com/about-lupron-depot/what-to-expect-during-therapy.cfm | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref> There are also other ailments and even dietary changes which can cause it <ref name="livestrong.com"/> Men who are [[castrated]] can also get hot flashes.<ref>{{cite web | title = Hot Flashes In Men -- Mayo Clinic Researchers Describe A Treatment | work = ScienceDaily   | publisher = Science Daily LLC | date = October 19, 2004 | url = http://sciencedaily.com/releases/2004/10/041019085808.htm | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Engstrom | first = Christine A. | last2 = Kasper | first2 = Christine E. | title = Physiology and Endocrinology of Hot Flashes in Prostate Cancer | journal = American Journal of Men’s Health | volume = 1 | issue = 1 | pages = 8-17 | publisher = Sage Publications | date = March 2007 | url = http://jmh.sagepub.com/content/1/1/8.abstract | doi = 10.1177/1557988306294162 | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Anitei | first = Stefan | title = Men Can Experience Hot Flashes, Just Like Women in Menopause | work = Softpedia | publisher = Softpedia   | date = April 16, 2007 | url = http://news.softpedia.com/news/Men-Can-Experience-Hot-Flashes-Like-Menopause-Women-52030.shtml | accessdate = April 20, 2013}}</ref>

== Regional variance ==
It has been speculated<ref>{{cite journal|last=Messina|first=Mark|coauthors=Claude Hughes|title=Efficacy of Soyfoods and Soybean Isoflavone Supplements for Alleviating Menopausal Symptoms Is Positively Related to Initial Hot Flush Frequency|journal=JOURNAL OF MEDICINAL FOOD|year=2003|volume=6|pages=2|accessdate=28 May 2011|publisher=Mary Ann Liebert, Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Lock|first=Margaret|title=Menopause in cultural context|journal=Experimental Gerontology|year=1994|month=May–August|volume=29|issue=3-4|pages=307–317|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0531556594900116|accessdate=28 May 2011|publisher=Elsevier Inc.|doi=10.1016/0531-5565(94)90011-6}}</ref>  that hot flashes are considerably less common among Asian women, possibly owing to their soy rich diets.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Penotti M, Fabio E, Bachhi A, Rinaldi M, Omodei U, Viganob P|title=Effect of soy-derived isoflavones on hot flushes, endometrial thickness, and the pulsatility index of the uterine and cerebral arteries|journal=Fertility and Sterility|year=2003|month=May|volume=79|issue=5|pages=1112–1117|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0015028203001584|publisher=Elsevier Inc.|doi=10.1016/S0015-0282(03)00158-4}}</ref>

